decreased. 
Disadvantages 
a   High initial cost and complicated system of laying 
ii   Gas pressure cables. The voltage required to set up 
ionization inside a void increases as the pressure is 
increased. Therefore, if ordinary cable is subjected to 
a   sufficiently high   pressure,   the ionization   can   be 
altogether eliminated. At the same time, the increased 
pressure produces radial compression which tends to 
 close any voids. This is the underlying principle of gas 
 pressure cables. 
Fig 9 shows the section of external pressure cable designed 
by Hockstadter, Vogal and Bowden.   The construction of 
the cable is similar to that an ordinary solid type except 
that itis of triangular shape and thickness of lead sheath 
is 75% that of solid cable. The triangular section reduces 
the weight and gives low thermal resistance but the main 
reason for triangular shape is that the lead sheath acts as 
a pressure membrane.   The sheath is protected by a thin 
metal tape.   The cable is laid is a gas-tight steel pipe. 
